    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1989377466" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1989377466" />
    <a title="Katrina" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5509524-katrina"><img alt="Katrina" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1321152897p2/5509524.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1989377466?book_show_action=true">May 27, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Katrina" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Katrina" href="/user/show/5509524-katrina">Katrina</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780312680466" href="/book/show/9229338-the-lost-books-of-the-odyssey">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5509524-katrina?shelf=owned">owned</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5509524-katrina?shelf=short-stories">short-stories</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5509524-katrina?shelf=signed">signed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5509524-katrina?shelf=mythology">mythology</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1989377466" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8330404115949271528">Unexpectedly gorgeous. I say &quot;unexpected&quot; because this is the type of book that could so easily come across as pretentious, overwhelmed by its author&apos;s ego...yet it was beautifully told, with luminous detail and oddly compelling, heavily intellectual creativity.<br/><br/>I don&apos;t know why I expected to be annoyed by the writing. Perhaps it&apos;s because the description and introduction made it sound like a McSweeney&apos;s article-turned-book, which...frankly, is not at all an appealing prospect for me. I&apos;m only no</span>
  <span id="freeText8330404115949271528" style="display:none">Unexpectedly gorgeous. I say "unexpected" because this is the type of book that could so easily come across as pretentious, overwhelmed by its author's ego...yet it was beautifully told, with luminous detail and oddly compelling, heavily intellectual creativity.<br /><br />I don't know why I expected to be annoyed by the writing. Perhaps it's because the description and introduction made it sound like a McSweeney's article-turned-book, which...frankly, is not at all an appealing prospect for me. I'm only noting this initial bias because when you <em>try</em> to find something irritating and instead end up completely charmed, that says a lot about the quality of the work. "Record of a Game," right near the end, did focus too heavily on its own cleverness for my taste, but the remainder proved to be one sparkling gem after another.<br /><br />The idea behind this collection is that "the Homeric material was formless, fluid, its elements shuffled into new narratives like cards in a deck." Mason plays with this format by laying out 44 vignettes that each tell some part of Odysseus's journey home from Troy - in disconnected, often contradictory narratives.<br /><br />Remarkably, the overall effect remains that of a single, coherent story. It turns the process of reading into an archaeological dig, in a way, as we slowly unearth fragments, piecing them together and rearranging them each time we discover more. In a version near the end of the set, Odysseus muses about his fading memories and the oral tradition that gradually reshapes stories. Did everything happen exactly as it was related? Perhaps not. How much does that matter? How much of the essence holds true when you peel back layers and shift sections into new forms?<br /><br />I've loved <em>The Odyssey</em> for many years, and any dip into mythology will always catch my attention and leave me eager to search for more. Mason's crackling intelligence and impeccable ear for language is a pleasure to read. And now I, as I <em>should</em> have expected, am craving other versions of these stories.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8330404115949271528" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

